We start by extracting the relevant figures from the provided statements.

1. Debt to Equity Ratio  
 • Total Liabilities can be calculated as:  
  Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 12,385,382.42 – 11,647,620.37  
  = 737,762.05  
 • Total Owner’s Equity (end) = 11,647,620.37  
 • Debt to Equity Ratio = 737,762.05 / 11,647,620.37 ≈ 0.0634  
 Rounded, we present this as 0.06.

2. Net Profit Margin  
 • Net Profit = –1,352,379.63  
 • Total Revenue (from income statement) = 5,755,241.17  
 • Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (–1,352,379.63 / 5,755,241.17) × 100 ≈ –23.48%

3. Return on Assets (ROA)  
 • ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100  
  = (–1,352,379.63 / 12,385,382.42) × 100 ≈ –10.92%

4. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
 • From the balance sheet, Accounts Receivable at end = 1,604,015.21. The beginning balance is 0, so the average Accounts Receivable = (0 + 1,604,015.21)/2 ≈ 802,007.61  
 • Using the Main Business Revenue (which is the appropriate proxy for net sales) of 5,755,241.17, the turnover ratio is:  
  = 5,755,241.17 / 802,007.61 ≈ 7.17

Presenting the results in the requested format:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.06",
    "Net Profit Margin": "-23.48%",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "-10.92%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "7.17"
  }
}
